      <h1 class="na-title">You Were Not Alone</h1>

      <div class="na-body">

        <p>I knew what I wanted the viewer to feel. Yearning. Not depicted — experienced. The way Beckett doesn't describe waiting in <em>Waiting for Godot</em>. He makes you wait. The structure creates the feeling.</p>

        <p>I had the intent. I didn't know my structure was working against it.</p>

        <p>That's the part artists don't talk about much. Not because it's rare — it's constant. You make work inside a kind of productive blindness. You know what you're reaching for. You can't always see what's fighting the reach.</p>

        <p>Normally, you'd take it to someone whose eye you trust. But there's a tax. You perform the coherent version of your thinking. Which means you get feedback on the performance, not the problem.</p>

        <hr class="na-rule">

        <p>I started using an AI differently. Not as a generator. As an interviewer.</p>

        <p>The idea comes from Jack Clark — co-founder of Anthropic, the company behind Claude, and someone who spends a lot of time thinking about what AI is actually good for — who described asking an AI to interview him about what he wanted to build before writing a single line of code. The output got better because the input was finally honest.</p>

        <p>I tried it with the painting.</p>

        <p>Questions came back. What was I trying to create? What experience did I want the viewer to have? What was I afraid wasn't working?</p>

        <p>That last one. With another person, I'd have deflected. With the AI, I just answered.</p>

        <hr class="na-rule">

        <p>What came back wasn't about medium. No pigment recommendations. No mark-making advice. A structural diagnosis: the edges were too defined. The painting was closed. Nothing was reaching.</p>

        <p>For a painting about yearning, that's fatal.</p>

        <p>Yearning needs an outside. Something beyond the frame the eye moves toward but can't reach. I needed to soften those edges — and redirect the foreground gaze past the canvas boundary. Toward the unreachable thing.</p>

        <p>Beckett's mechanism exactly. Godot never comes. The edge stays open. Absence is the engine.</p>

        <p>My painting had definition where it needed ambiguity. It completed a world when it needed to leave one open.</p>

        <hr class="na-rule">

        <p>The AI didn't make the painting. It named what was working against my intent. I still had to solve it.</p>

        <p>But the reason it worked is the same reason it couldn't have worked as well with another person. No stakes. No performance. I could say where my thinking was uncertain — where I suspected I was wrong — without the cost of looking that way in front of someone whose opinion of me matters.</p>

        <p>The AI kept my secrets. The secret being, mostly, that I didn't entirely know what I was doing.</p>

        <p>That's not a failure condition. That's just making.</p>

        <hr class="na-rule">

        <p>What the AI gave me wasn't a solution. It gave me a question I could finally answer honestly.</p>

        <p>That's what a trusted companion does.</p>

      </div>

